<div id="review_48125139" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/48125139" />
    <a title="Eileen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/144886-eileen"><img alt="Eileen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1186165493p2/144886.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/48125139?book_show_action=true">Mar 03, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eileen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eileen" href="/user/show/144886-eileen">Eileen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/144886-eileen?shelf=justplaingoodreading">justplaingoodreading</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer48125139" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12366843470277767349">This incredibly well-written novel is not the typical - if you&apos;ll forgive calling a Holocaust survival story &apos;typical&apos; - story of a survivor of WWII. The perspective is that of a Jewish boy in Poland who never sees a concentration camp, but lives a different kind of trauma in hiding his Jewish identity throughout the war. The novel addresses many complexities, but for me ultimately raised questions of &quot;honorable&quot; choice: is there more honor in surviving a war, and in this case escaping the worst</span>
  <span id="freeText12366843470277767349" style="display:none">This incredibly well-written novel is not the typical - if you'll forgive calling a Holocaust survival story 'typical' - story of a survivor of WWII. The perspective is that of a Jewish boy in Poland who never sees a concentration camp, but lives a different kind of trauma in hiding his Jewish identity throughout the war. The novel addresses many complexities, but for me ultimately raised questions of "honorable" choice: is there more honor in surviving a war, and in this case escaping the worst atrocity, one way versus another? How does the unsentimental practicality inherent in a survivor's generation impact a child? What does it mean to be a survivor on the fringe of a community already on the periphery? Highly recommended - also a quick read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12366843470277767349" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


