  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3795311409" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3795311409" />
    <a title="Chris" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/128945505-chris"><img alt="Chris" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611352036p2/128945505.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3795311409?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris" href="/user/show/128945505-chris">Chris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128945505-chris?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3795311409" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14665510443732476163">Returning to an old book is like meeting an old friend. You always wonder if what had made you friends is still there, or have you changed so much that after reminiscing only silence ensues?<br/><br/>I read Wartime Lies a couple of times, but I honestly didn’t remember much of the story nor my general impression. Although some parts came back, nothing was vivid, whereas other books remain so. I can talk about the characters, plot, and prose of other books with relative ease. Wartime Lies wasn’t quite like</span>
  <span id="freeText14665510443732476163" style="display:none">Returning to an old book is like meeting an old friend. You always wonder if what had made you friends is still there, or have you changed so much that after reminiscing only silence ensues?<br /><br />I read Wartime Lies a couple of times, but I honestly didn’t remember much of the story nor my general impression. Although some parts came back, nothing was vivid, whereas other books remain so. I can talk about the characters, plot, and prose of other books with relative ease. Wartime Lies wasn’t quite like reading a new book, but it was close.<br /><br />The books narrates a realistic, but not visceral, account of a young boy in hiding during WWII. Told from his perspective, it nevertheless feels a lot as though he heard the tale secondhand. He is removed. And to some degree, this makes sense, as supported by the final sentences where the protagonist says the lie subsumed him and he bears no connection to the boy. “Is there much of Maciek in that man? No: Maciek was a child, and our man has no childhood [...]; he has had to invent one.” There seems an emotional disconnect between the narrator and his actions, and as a result, the reader.<br /><br />Overall, I still thought it an enjoyable break from my recent nonfiction choices.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14665510443732476163" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

