<div id="review_49213619" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/49213619" />
    <a title="Scott E" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1177500-scott-e"><img alt="Scott E" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1229543969p2/1177500.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/49213619?book_show_action=true">Mar 13, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott E" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott E" href="/user/show/1177500-scott-e">Scott E</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1177500-scott-e?shelf=read-fiction">read-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer49213619" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14530464221947856957">The first I&apos;ve read by Begley, and his first...not a bad place to start. A nine year old Jewish boy forced to grow up quickly as he and his aunt are on the run attempting to avoid the Nazis. Told the boy&apos;s perspective, there isn&apos;t a great deal of Nazi atrocity...but still enough to piss you off and make you want to grind the broken end of a coke bottle into Hitler&apos;s throat. But I digress.<br/><br/>Begley tells the story with little sentimentality. This is almost a coming of age story, and I wonder if any </span>
  <span id="freeText14530464221947856957" style="display:none">The first I've read by Begley, and his first...not a bad place to start. A nine year old Jewish boy forced to grow up quickly as he and his aunt are on the run attempting to avoid the Nazis. Told the boy's perspective, there isn't a great deal of Nazi atrocity...but still enough to piss you off and make you want to grind the broken end of a coke bottle into Hitler's throat. But I digress.<br /><br />Begley tells the story with little sentimentality. This is almost a coming of age story, and I wonder if any of it is autobiographical (I haven't read anything about Begley to know). There is a sort of history lesson here and we are witness to the destruction of the Warsaw ghettos and then Warsaw itself.<br /><br />It was a quick read (two days), and probably not quite up to the 4-stars I gave it....more like a 3.8.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14530464221947856957" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


